The paper deals with matrix completion, which is a common problem in machine learning and data analysis. The approach taken in the paper involves recovering the column space of the matrix from fully observed columns and then using this information to recover partially observed columns. This suggests that the paper is likely to be relevant to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG), as well as information theory (cs.IT) and numerical analysis (cs.NA). Additionally, the use of random sampling and low-rank matrix recovery techniques suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and social and information networks (cs.SI).
